<TEXT>
usbacked nicaraguan contra 
rebels agree to begin immediate disbanding of their forces in 
honduras breaking a deadlock in the way of the peaceful transition 
of power in their homeland 
the agreement reached friday after talks by the contras 
cardinal miguel obando y bravo and representatives of 
presidentelect violeta barrios de chamorro was praised by 
president daniel ortega whose sandinistas have fought the rebels 
for nine years 
this is an accord that recognizes a national consensus and 
this national consensus that will put an end to the war and bring 
peace to nicaragua ortega said in managua the nicaraguan 
capital 
the contras agreed friday to begin demobilizing the 12000 
troops in honduran base camps immediately and said they should all 
be back in nicaragua by april 20 five days before mrs chamorros 
prous government is inaugurated the contras said another 4000 
fighters in nicaragua would move into security zones 
the accord was announced in tegucigalpa by obando y bravo the 
roman catholic archbishop of managua 
a communique issued at the end of the sevenhour talks said the 
usbacked contras were ready to disband because the feb 25 
general elections had established a process of democratization 
in nicaragua 
ortega mrs chamorro and president bush who has asked congress 
for a 300 million aid package that includes 45 million for 
demobilization have all called upon the rebels to disband 
the agreement to dismantle the contras appears to remove the 
biggest stumbling block to the transfer of power 
the outgoing sandinista government had said they could not 
relinquish control of the armed forces as long as the contras 
refused to demobilize the senior contra military commander israel 
galeano had said the rebels wouldnt put down their guns as long 
as the sandinistas kept theirs 
ortega was at the airport to greet the cardinal and mrs 
chamorros negotiators when they returned to managua friday night 
from the honduran capital 
i am going to give instructions immediately to the foreign 
ministry and the defense ministry to take steps to apply the letter 
of this accord he told a news conference it is possible that 
there wont be a single armed contra in nicaragua on april 25th 
but ortega also said he was concerned that galeano had not 
signed the accord 
we hope that this accord will be accepted and respected by all 
members of the contra who are in nicaraguan territory and that we 
can save the nicaraguan people from a bloodbath he said 
antonio lacayo one of mrs chamorros negotiators said it is 
up to the contras to make sure galeano respects the accord 
ortega said there were between 4000 and 6000 contra rebels 
inside nicaragua preparing for a major military offensive for the 
days prior to the inauguration the demobilization accord should 
put an end to any plans for an offensive he said 
the head of the contra negotiating team said 12000 rebels 
living in base camps in yamales honduras along with 42000 
relatives would be home by april 20 
the nicaraguan resistance begins its return to nicaragua 
today rebel negotiator oscar sovalbarro said the process 
will culminate on april 20 with the goal of reincorporating its 
members into the civilian society 
another 4000 contras in nicaragua would move into security 
zones supervised by obando y bravo and the united nations which 
has observer and demobilization missions in the region he said 
the agreement calls for an immediate ceasefire to be monitored 
by the united nations and obando y bravo who said the sandinistas 
should cease attacks on the rebels as a gesture of good faith 
toward the pact 
we trust in obando y bravos moral force sovalbarro said 
mrs chamorros team promised pensions for contra widows and 
orphans and to wounded rebel veterans in recognition of their 
patriotic labors 
the chamorro delegation also agreed to set up a commission 
including representatives of the new government and of the contras 
to monitor demobilization 
the commission and humanitarian aid for the rebels and their 
families were conditions the contras set for demobilization at the 
outset of fridays talks 
the rebels went into the talks with a long list of demands 
including several such as the demobilization of the sandinista 
army that would have required the agreement of the sandinistas 
the sandinistas were not represented at the talks 
ortega agreed to the feb 25 elections which were monitored by 
several thousand international observers as part of a central 
america accord on demobilizing the contras 
within hours of her upset victory mrs chamorro had called upon 
the rebels to disband saying the democracy they had been fighting 
for had arrived in nicaragua and there was no longer any reason to 
fight 
