<TEXT>
a democratic study says defense secretary dick 
cheneys proposal to close military bases as a costsaving measure 
is an attempt to divert attention from an inflated defense budget 
the report released friday criticized the bush administration 
for its 307 billion fiscal 1991 defense budget that increases 
spending over last year including money for strategic weapons such 
as the b2 stealth bomber 
in the face of dramatic changes in the external threat faced 
by the united states the president has proposed nominal growth in 
defense spending for not only the coming year but for the 
foreseeable future the democratic study group said in its report 
the pentagon has argued that the budget fails to keep pace with 
the 21 percent increase in inflation 
the study faults cheney for requesting new legislation to close 
military facilities thus ending the congressional oversight of 
pentagon decisions on the bases and bypassing the recent process in 
which an independent commission recommended which bases to close 
complicating matters was cheneys january announcement of the 
candidates for closure or realignment before the department had 
completed its review the study said 
the administrations alternative process involves listing 
bases being considered for closing long before final decisions 
are made thereby creating maximum opportunity for fullblown 
lobbying campaigns against possible cutbacks the study said 
cheneys recommendations called for closing or scaling back more 
than 72 domestic facilities and 14 overseas installations members 
of congress including rep les aspin dwis chairman of the 
house armed services committee have criticized cheneys list as 
partisan 
the defense secretary has declined to give exact figures on the 
savings from the base closings 
the study the great base closing ploy creating a political 
tempest to shield a bloated defense budget said that 19 of 21 
proposed base closings are in democratic districts 
of the 41638 civilian jobs affected by the closings 41139 
or 99 percent were in democratic districts the report said 
the pentagon in response to the partisan charge noted that 
democrats are the majority party in the house 
