<TEXT>
new regulations proposed by the department of 
health and human services would put the burden on states to ensure 
that the mentally ill and mentally retarded get appropriate care in 
nursing homes 
the proposal friday would put into effect a law passed by 
congress in 1987 requiring states to set up programs to screen 
nursing home applicants and find more appropriate placements for 
mentally ill and mentally retarded applicants who do not need 
nursing facility care 
another proposed regulation would require nursing homes to meet 
new training and competency standards for nurse aides 
the screening requirement took effect jan 1 1989 although no 
regulations were in place the health care financing administration 
notified state medicaid directors at the time that compliance was 
required and provided preliminary guidance to the states 
failure of a nursing home to meet the terms of the screening 
requirement could result in its termination from the medicaid 
program 
the proposed rule outlines the specific details of the 
preadmission screening programs and requires an annual review of 
current nursing home residents with mental illness and retardation 
