<TEXT>
important events in the conflict 
between nicaraguas governing sandinistas and the ussupported 
contra rebels 
july 19 1979 the sandinista national liberation front enters 
managua two days after dictator anastasio somoza flees 
november 1980 first attacks by antisandinistas who become 
known as contras short for the spanish word for 
counterrevolutionary 
february 1981 reagan administration suspends aid to the 
leftist sandinistas 
november 1982 first reports emerge of covert us aid to the 
contras 
april 67 1984 commandos operating from us ships plant 
mines in nicaraguan ports 
april 9 nicaragua asks the world court to order the united 
states to stop helping the contras the reagan administration 
refuses to recognize the courts jurisdiction 
may 1 1985 reagan announces trade embargo against nicaragua 
june 27 the world court says us support of the contras 
violates the un charters ban on use of force 
june 25 1986 house approves 100 million in military and 
humanitarian aid to contras 
aug 13 the us senate approves military aid package 
oct 5 an americanmanned cargo plane is shot down over 
nicaragua surviving crew member eugene hasenfus is captured and 
implicates the cia in contrasupply operations hasenfus is 
subsequently freed 
nov 25 us attorney general edwin meese says some profits 
from the sale of american arms to iran were secretly diverted to 
the contras in an operation under marine lt col oliver north 
aug 7 1987 five central american presidents sign a regional 
peace plan that calls for an end to foreign aid for irregular 
forces and prohibits one country from allowing its territory to be 
used by guerrillas to attack another country 
feb 3 1988 congress cuts off military aid to the contras but 
continues other aid 
april 1 1988 a formal 60day truce begins following first 
direct meeting between sandinistas and contras 
may 31 the sandinistas decide to extend the ceasefire on a 
monthtomonth basis the contras say they consider the truce 
indefinite fighting slackens 
september contrasandinista talks break down thousands of 
contra guerrillas begin moving out of the nicaraguan hinterland 
into base camps in honduras 
feb 14 1989 five central american presidents agree the 
contras should be demobilized in exchange ortega agrees to free 
and fair elections in 1990 
april 28 president bush signs a 49 million nonlethal aid 
package for the contras that will run out three days after the 1990 
elections 
aug 7 the central american presidents formalize the 
demobilization accord asking the united nations and the 
organization of american states for help but the rebels are not 
signatories to the pact which says demobilization must be 
voluntary 
aug 26 contra commander israel galeano says the rebels will 
ignore the demobilization accord and us advice and starts moving 
his troops back to nicaragua 
nov 1 ortega lifts the 19monthold ceasefire after several 
attacks and the infiltration of thousands of contra troops 
fighting surges briefly 
dec 12 ortega and four central american presidents issue a 
communique calling for the demobilization of both the salvadoran 
guerrillas and the contras 
feb 25 1990 elections monitored by thousands of 
international observers are held ortega suffers a stunning upset 
at the hands of a nation weary of war and economic ruin 
feb 27 the sandinistas say the contras have to demobilize 
before they will hand over control of the police and armed forces 
presidentelect violeta barrios de chamorro calls on the contras to 
disband saying the elections mean there is no reason to keep on 
fighting 
march 8 ortega warns that thousands of armed sandinista 
supporters will rise up in arms if the contras dont lay down their 
arms 
march 13 president bush lifts the economic embargo and asks 
congress for 300 million in aid including 45 million to 
demobilize and relocate the contras 
friday the contras agree to disband their 12000 troops in 
