<TEXT>
the last indian peacekeeping 
soldiers withdrew from sri lanka today after 30 months of a 
stalemated jungle war against tamil guerrillas 
a sri lankan naval band played auld lang syne and sri 
lankan soldiers unsheathed swords in a guard of honor for the 
departing indians who came to enforce an agreement supposed to end 
the guerrilla war 
about 2000 soldiers the last to be withdrawn from a force 
that once numbered 125000 sailed from from the eastern city of 
trincomalee for madras in southern india 
you have made a great sacrifice there is no doubt about 
that sri lankas defense minister ranjan wijeratne told the 
camouflageuniformed troops 
at least 1155 soldiers died fighting guerrillas of the 
liberation tigers of tamil eelam the largest militant group 
demanding an independent tamil nation 
the indian troops arrived in northern and eastern sri lanka in 
july 1987 under an indiasri lanka accord to disarm the tamil 
tigers and several other tamil separatist militant groups 
while most groups surrendered their arms the tamil tigers 
reneged on the accord in october 1987 and turned their guns on the 
indian soldiers who had once trained them the tigers claimed the 
provisions of the accord which promised limited autonomy did not 
meet their aspirations 
as the jungle war continued india sent more reinforcements at 
one point about 125000 soldiers patrolled the northeast 
last summer the new government of president ranasinghe premadasa 
reached an agreement with the tigers and asked india to pull out 
its troops by july 29 1989 the second anniversary of the peace 
accord 
at that time indian forces controlled most of the larger towns 
in northern and eastern sri lanka but the tamil tigers ran an 
effective underground movement from the dense jungles and swamps 
new delhi stalled on the withdrawal request for about six 
months leading to diplomatic standoff between officials of the two 
countries 
in january after the new indian government of prime minister 
vp singh took office india and sri lanka agreed on a march 31 
deadline 
the long stay brought severe criticism in both sri lanka and 
india many indian newspapers said the troops were needlessly 
fighting somebody elses dirty war 
weve been ordered to leave and thats what we are doing 
said a commando at the trincomalee dock pushing back his red beret 
to wipe sweat from his forehead we dont think we have lost a 
war were just obeying orders 
across the bay from where magar sailed tamil tigers patrolled 
trincomalees streets accompanied by sri lankan soldiers and 
police the forces which desperately tried to put down the tamil 
rebellion between 1983 until the indians arrival in 1987 
in recent months the tamil tigers have joined other groups in 
negotiations with the sri lankan government 
tamils who make up 18 percent of sri lankas 16 million people 
wanted to set up a separate homeland in the northern and eastern 
districts where most of the countrys tamils live the tamils 
claimed they were discriminated in jobs education and the use of 
sinhala language by the majroity sinhalese 
the predominantly buddhist sinhalese make up 75 percent of the 
population and control the government and the military tamils are 
mostly hindus 
besides the indian troop casualties 10000 sri lankans have 
died in the tamil insurgency in addition the 1987 peace accord 
