today 
the sparsely populated desert region in chinas northwest is 
home to 25 different minority groups including several large 
moslem groups who account for 62 percent of xinjiangs population 
amudun niyazi chairman of the xinjiang peoples congress 
standing committee told the associated press that there has been 
no violence in the region so far 
but he said authorities recently have discovered handbills 
leaflets and other materials instigating separatist activities 
circulating through the region one of chinas largest ethnic 
minority areas 
niyazi said most of the material has come from former xinjiang 
residents now living overseas but declined to provide other 
details 
in the past few months news reports from xinjiang have hinted 
of ethnic trouble editorials and commentaries stressing the need 
for unity and stability and denouncing separatist activities 
have increased markedly 
china violently imposed its rule on the region in the 1950s 
slaughtering those who took part in antichinese revolts 
since then the ethnic groups have largely accepted beijings 
domination although tensions remain and ethnic trouble has 
surfaced from time to time 
the largest ethnic groups include the moslem uygur and kazakh 
minorities central asian groups with close ties to people living 
across the border in the soviet union 
