<TEXT>
bias against women in the california 
justice system is often blatant sometimes subtle and apparent in 
the sharp contrast between the opinions of female and male judges 
a state report found 
the report released friday said gender bias in the state would 
decline if the proportion of women judges increased above the 
current 13 percent a figure already nearly twice the national 
average 
the gender bias that we have found in the judicial system 
reflects the society said los angeles county superior court 
judge david rothman cochair of a state judicial council committee 
that produced the study 
as judges we have an obligation to do something about it he 
said 
a theme common to many of the findings was the lack of 
credibility with which women are regarded in the courts said los 
angeles county superior court judge judith chirlin vicechair of 
the study 
she said bias shows up in many ways judges who call a male 
expert witness doctor but ask a woman with the same credentials 
whether she prefers miss or ms another tendency by many 
male judges is to doubt womens stories that their husbands beat 
them or molested their children 
the report offered 65 recommendations including simplifying and 
speeding up procedures for restraining orders against domestic 
violence improving health care for female prisoners and putting 
antibias provisions into the judges code of conduct the law 
school curriculum and the bar exam 
the study was begun in 1986 by chief justice rose bird and 
continued by successor malcolm lucas after birds defeat in the 
1986 election 
the study cited a survey last year of 473 california judges that 
showed some sharp differences in attitudes between men and women on 
the bench 
forty percent of the male judges but only 22 percent of the 
women thought domestic violence cases should be dealt with by 
counseling instead of prosecution 47 percent men but 75 percent 
women disagreed with a statement that domestic violence allegations 
were often exaggerated 7 percent men but 45 percent women said 
they had heard other judges make remarks demeaning to women 
many of those comments were chronicled most of them 
anonymously a male judge who told a female lawyer not to try any 
of your feminine tricks any of your emotionalism another who 
asked two women lawyers if theyd had a cat fight others who 
invariably asked the woman in a group of lawyers if she could type 
up a settlement agreement 
the study said demeaning comments were more likely to come from 
lawyers than judges committee members speaking to reporters also 
said individual remarks by judges however shocking were not as 
pervasive a problem as others covered by the report such as the 
difficulties encountered by women in divorce courts domestic 
violence cases and prisons 
most of the gender bias is institutionalized watson said 
for example she said members visiting the main womens jail in 
los angeles county found pregnant women who had not seen a doctor 
for four months they also said mothers awaiting trial for a year 
were not told where their children had been placed and were given 
only one change of underwear a week 
chirlin said another important finding was the low status and 
relatively meager budgets of family law courts 
any issues relating to families and kids are quote womens 
issues and are seen as less important she said the report 
urges an increase in family court judges and a study of the 
adequacy of child support levels 
