an wang the slight chineseborn engineer whose 
development of a major computer firm was a classic american success 
story died today at massachusetts general hospital after a long 
fight against cancer at age 70 
hospital spokesman martin bander said wang died at 531 am 
he was operated on originally on july 14 of last year for 
esophageal cancer a very difficult form of cancer bander said 
he was admitted to the mass general cancer center on march 6 
after suffering some setback 
he began wang laboratories in 1951 above an electrical fixtures 
store in boston with a work force of one himself 
wang went on to develop the magnetic core a small 
doughnutshaped ring of iron that was the basic element of computer 
memory until the microchip was introduced in the late 1960s 
a native of shanghai wang was a schoolteachers son who had 
come to the united states in 1945 and went to harvard as a graduate 
student 
when his firm began to grow quickly wang moved it northwest of 
boston to lowell the growth of wang laboratories took off in 1964 
after he introduced a desktop calculator and began development of 
office computers 
once rated the fifthrichest man in america wang spread jobs to 
other areas and the company now has about 23000 employees 
worldwide 
his wife lorraine sons fred and courtney and daughter 
juliette had been at his hospital bedside regularly during his 
hospitalization according to company spokesman paul guzzi 
