wheelwright high school may be tucked in 
a remote corner of rural eastern kentucky but these days its 
students are trading information and greetings with counterparts 
everywhere from homer alaska to bogota and london 
but these modernday penpals are communicating by computer not 
paper and pen 
kisha cotton 17 wrote about growing up in a rural appalachian 
hollow and her first encounter with racism at a beauty pagent the 
essay was posted on a computer bulletin board and read by students 
across the world miss cotton who is black was astonished at some 
of the responses 
some of the kids said they never met a black person or got a 
letter from one said miss cotton some of the kids didnt know 
black kids went to school with white kids 
the experience will help her handle racism when she leaves home 
for college next fall she said 
the computer conferences some carefully structured around a 
single subject others more loosely organized to allow students to 
communicate on various topics are organized by the breadnet 
computer network based at middlebury college in vermont schools 
use their own computers to link up with the central computer at 
middlebury 
a core group of about 60 schools is taking part in the general 
program while other schools are taking part in singletopic 
conferences said hugh coyle administrative director of 
middleburys bread loaf school of english 
students at wheelwright high are amoung about 70 groups around 
the world currently involved in a conference on environmental 
issues called world class said william w wright jr 
breadnet director 
it does bring some of the kids alive it engages them and 
sparks active learning said wright using technology this way 
has engaged students in a way that video does not 
the participants here shared some of the messages received from 
other countries some students in toronto canada facetiously 
noted that its hard to imagine that inside our freezing igloos 
we find space for a computer they added that they were taking 
part in the environmental exchange to make the world a better and 
cleaner place 
while the canadians cited concerns about acid rain a group of 
geography students from the united arab emirates sent in 
information about the land and history of the middle east and the 
environmental problems raised by rapid population growth and 
pollution generated by the oil industry 
conferences run several weeks and follow a structured format 
students read magazine articles and work in groups to pose 
questions for experts or answer queries from other students the 
teams also use the network to research a specific topic such as 
depletion of the earths ozone layer 
they send facts we dont know about and we send facts they 
dont know about said haley caudill 18 gathered with what we 
have it really helps with a better understanding 
sen albert gore dtenn will be an online guest monday 
