spaces are not startling 
people visiting the museum for the first time probably wont 
notice so much he said 
considered too wellknown to be sold on to a legitimate 
collector the haul from mrs gardners collection has been 
estimated to be worth hundreds of millions of dollars 
investigators offer several theories on why the treasures were 
stolen 
a private collector with a penchant for the priceless might have 
commissioned the theft a sort of dr no scenario that curators 
say is mostly the stuff of spy novels the lesserknown works might 
be sold on the black market and resurface in respectable galleries 
in a few years 
or most likely the thieves might ransom the treasures either 
for the reward or for insurance money though gardner officials 
revealed this week that the works were not insured for theft 
what is worrisome is that jumbo art heists seem to be increasing 
in both scale and frequency as art prices soar on the legal market 
the loss in just a few recent thefts is staggering 
oct 27 1985 five armed men steal nine impressionist 
paintings by painters such as monet renoir and berthe morisot from 
the marmottan museum in paris one of the paintings impression 
sunrise is the work that gave impressionism its name the take 
125 million at 1985 prices 
may 21 1986 thieves steal 18 paintings including vermeers 
lady writing a letter with her maid from russborough house in 
blessington ireland the take 40 million 
feb 8 1988 burglars break through a skylight into the 
colnaghi art gallery in new york city and steal 27 old master 
paintings and drawings the take 6 million 
security consultants say museums are lagging in efforts to 
prevent art theft guards hired to protect multimilliondollar 
paintings often are paid little more than minimum wage and given 
scant training 
in addition only a handful of police or federal agents across 
the country are trained to investigate art heists and 
international laws make it easy to transport works across national 
borders 
theres no duty on art lowenthal said you couldnt just 
bring 20 million in cash into the country but you could bring in 
a painting worth that much 
the biggest problem in the long run lowenthal said is that as 
more priceless works are stolen and art prices grow ever higher 
museums wont be able to replace the art they lose 
museums just cant afford to replace expensive works 
lowenthal said you can always get another warhol print you 
cant replace a vermeer 
