west german foreign minister 
hansdietrich genscher saturday signed an agreement that abolishes 
the visa requirement between his country and hungary 
he also presented a merit award to foreign minister gyula horn 
apparently for hungarys decision to open its borders last year to 
east germans seeking a better life in the west the exodus of east 
germans sparked the peaceful revolution that led to east germanys 
first free elections last weekend 
hungarians were to go to the polls sunday for their first free 
multiparty elections in 43 years of communist rule 
visafree travel between west germany a member of nato and 
hungary a member of the sovietled warsaw pact goes into effect 
may 1 
genscher and horn also signed three other bilateral agreements 
on education and management training for hungarians 
it remains unforgotten that hungary was the first to cut the 
iron curtain genscher told horn after the signing ceremony 
hungary began dismantling the barbed wire barriers along its 
western border with austria in may the open border was used by 
thousands of east germans fed up with 40 years of hardline 
communist rule to flee to west germany via austria 
as hungary stood valiantly by our side in a difficult hour of 
our history we will not leave hungary in the lurch on her way to 
democracy and a market economy genscher said 
addressing a concern that has dominated the hungarian election 
campaign the past few days genscher also said he hoped the rights 
of minorities including those of the ethnic hungarians in romania 
would be respected 
hungarians feel a sense of kinship for the estimated 17 million 
ethnic hungarians in transylvania an area that belonged to hungary 
for centuries before being ceded to romania after world war i 
