an agreement to disband the contra 
rebels was in doubt saturday because the outgoing sandinista 
government had not signed the pact and because of renewed fighting 
the accord signed friday in tegucigalpa honduras by 
representatives of the usbacked rebels and the new government 
calls for a truce and immediate disbanding of the contras the 
process would be completed before presidentelect violeta barrios 
de chamorro takes office april 25 for a sixyear term 
however no delegates from the sandinista government took part 
in talks that led to the pact or signed the accord 
also there has been renewed fighting in the past week between 
sandinista and contra forces and one rebel commander said his 
fighters will not lay down their arms until the sandinista army 
does 
the latest clash occurred friday when about 100 rebels ambushed 
two army vehicles in the area around jinotega a town about 100 
miles northeast of managua the defense ministry said 12 soldiers 
died and eight were wounded four contras were killed the ministry 
said 
medical sources who spoke on condition of anonymity said in a 
telephone interview that the attack occurred about the time the 
accord was being announced in tegucigalpa 
president daniel ortega has repeatedly said the contras must 
disband before mrs chamorros inauguration if there is to be a 
peaceful transfer of power 
after learning of the accord ortega told a rally of youth 
supporters in managua late friday that the weapons are now in the 
hands of the people 
ortega quoted saturday by the sandinista newspaper barricada 
did not elaborate but his remark seemed to be a reference to 
recent reports that the sandinista army had distributed hundreds of 
weapons among supporters in the provinces there have also been 
reports that the sandinista army will not yield control to the new 
government 
