nelson mandela said saturday 
the countrys black farm laborers are being exploited and called on 
rural towns to end segregated public facilities 
no white farmer has yet gone to prison for the murder of one 
of their workers nor will that happen for as long as farmers 
continue to enjoy the protection of local police and magistrates 
the antiapartheid leader said at an african national congress 
rally in nelspruit 
he cited the case of a white farmer who was recently fined only 
34 after his black worker died as a result of a beating 
mandela said the white towns in eastern transvaal province 
where he spoke were deeply racist and should immediately end 
segregation of recreational areas and other public facilities 
the government announced friday it intends to allow statefunded 
schools to become multiracial by january if 90 percent of the 
parents at a particular school favor the move 
president fw de klerk has been pushing a series of racial 
reforms he has called for ending the apartheid system of racial 
segregation and for holding talks on allowing the black majority an 
equal political role with whites 
de klerk has also said the law allowing municipalities to 
segregate public facilities would be repealed this year 
in february the president released mandela who had been in 
prison since 1962 on a life sentence for sabotage and plotting to 
overthrow the white government 
mandela vice president of the anc has been campaigning 
virtually nonstop since then for an end to apartheid 
at saturdays rally he called for an end to the land tenancy 
system that allows farmers to require the entire families of black 
laborers to work he condemned the lack of legal protection for 
farm workers and said they should be allowed full trade union 
rights 
