president mikhail s gorbachev on saturday named 
his key communist party aides to a new presidential advisory 
council in a move to transfer political power from the party to the 
government 
the top advisers foreign minister eduard a shevardnadze and 
alexander n yakovlev as well as the chiefs of the military and 
secret police are among five members of the partys ruling 
politburo selected for the presidential council 
the official tass news agency said gorbachev also picked two 
wellknown writers an economist and two parliamentarians to serve 
on the council 
although gorbachev assumed the position of president more than a 
year ago real power remained with the party 
the party has been controlled by its central committee of a few 
hundred of the party elite the top leaders in the moscowbased 
politburo and gorbachev himself as general secretary 
however the party has been under attack from many quarters for 
its handling of the economy and other matters earlier this year 
it renounced its 70year monopoly on power 
by presidential decree the new council will be housed in the 
kremlin where gorbachev also will have his presidential office 
new constitutional amendments establishing a strong presidency 
provide for the presidents appointment of a presidential council 
to be responsible for implementing the major lines of domestic 
and foreign policy and ensuring the security of the country 
the prime minister nikolai i ryzhkov is the only exofficio 
member of the council there is no fixed number of appointees nor 
any requirement that council members meet as a group 
but the council offers gorbachev a mechanism for bringing his 
chosen aides and advisers into the government instead of relying 
on their positions in the party leadership to give them regular 
access to him 
in addition to ryzhkov shevardnadze and yakovlev the panel 
will be composed of yuri d maslyukov head of the state planning 
committee which controls the centrally planned economy vladimir 
a kryuchkov chairman of the kgb gen dmitri t yazov the 
minister of defense albert kauls and venyamin yarin of the 
congress of peoples deputies writers valentin rasputin and 
chingiz aitmatov of kirghizia and economist stanislav s shatalin 
kauls runs the adazhi agricultural production firm in riga 
latvia that has been cited as a model for moving from a centrally 
planned to a market economy yarin is a worker at a steelmaking 
complex in nizhni tagil in the ural mountains 
