<TEXT>
the capitals halfdozen timekeepers worked 
furiously saturday to set 2500 public clocks an hour ahead but 
the industry minister thinks its time europe did away with the 
daylightsavings ritual 
france and the 11 other nations of the european community added 
one hour to their clocks at 2 am sunday to take advantage of an 
extra hour of evening sunlight through the summer 
industry minister roger faroux however wants to end the 
practice citing a recent ministry report showing the benefits are 
nil and that nearly half the population dislikes the change 
the french like less and less being told what hour to get up 
and what hour to sleep faroux was quoted as saying in saturdays 
editions of the newspaper le parisien its rude to impose 
changes on citizens in their private lives 
france went to daylightsavings time in 1976 along with belgium 
the netherlands luxembourg and spain as an energysavings measure 
to deal with the oil crisis 
the european community has coordinated the practice among 
members so that their clocks get turned forward the last sunday of 
march the agreement expires next year however and faroux wants 
france to lobby the ec to keep clocks on one 24hour cycle all year 
long 
faroux says the amount of energy saved by daylightsavings time 
is negligible now that france is powered mostly by nuclear energy 
last october he asked the national assembly to open an 
investigation into the benefits of the extra hour 
a survey conducted during the investigation showed 44 percent of 
french citizens oppose daylightsavings time and 57 percent feel it 
has not improved their quality of life 
an end to the twiceannual change could find favor with paris 
six official clockkeepers they make a twoday 435mile circuit 
twice a year to reset hands and bells and keep the capitals 2500 
clocks on the hour 
the parisians are really picky about time said chief 
clockkeeper marc bintz one pendulum badly set can set off a 
miniscandal in a neighborhood 
</TEXT>
