<TEXT>
indian tribes from the united states and 
canada gathered saturday to sign a firstever intertribal treaty 
rallying them to protect tribal rights and preserve their treaties 
with the government 
the document was drafted in response to fears that federal 
state and local governments intend to disregard their rights as 
sovereign nations and undermine treaties which grant the tribes 
land hunting rights and sovereign jurisdiction 
representatives of 20 indian nations or tribes many wearing 
traditional tribal headdresses signed the indigenous nations 
treaty during a twohour outdoor ceremony each briefly grasped a 
prayer staff before putting pen to paper 
afterwards a ceremonial peace pipe brought by the sioux nation 
was passed to the beat of tomtoms and prayer songs 
the document promises tribes will set aside differences and come 
to the defense of more than 400 treaties signed between the us 
government and indian tribes or nations over the past 200 years 
luke duncan chairman of utahs ute tribe said the peace pipe 
ceremony makes the document sacred 
this is an important day said wendel chino chairman of the 
mescalero apache tribe in new mexico who said past treaties 
deserve the same consideration as the us constitution or the bill 
of rights 
we alone know what it means when the drums beat he said 
that is why we must rally around our treaties let us say no 
to the subtle attempts to modify them 
the ceremony took place the same day the puyallup tribe in 
tacoma wash signed away its claim to a valuable chunk of 
industrial land in a settlement that will give the tribe 162 
million in cash education and job assistance and improvements to 
the land the tribe retains 
at the utah gathering tribal leaders said they hope their 
alliance will lead to a summit with president bush where concerns 
over federal encroachment into tribal sovereignty could be 
discussed 
today we remember the deaths of our chiefs our warriors our 
women and children said glen miller vicechairman of the 
menominee tribe of wisconsin he was one of several speakers in a 
morning session held following a flag ceremony and prayer songs 
today we remember the price they paid for our reservations 
he said our chiefs negotiated for peace and they were killed 
our women ran with their children and were killed 
we must soothe their bones revive their spirits and save 
their nation 
it was the second gathering in a month as tribal officials 
attempt to focus attention on the issue 
indian leaders met in south dakota last month to discuss 
strategy after a controversial gathering in salt lake city last 
january by local government officials meeting as part of the 
national coalition on federal indian policy worried about tribal 
influences 
that meeting was sponsored by the wisconsin association of 
counties 
the menominee tribe of wisconsin is battling the county 
association over timber and fishing rights 
there are things happening that make my heart feel heavy 
said paul iron cloud former president of the oglala sioux from the 
pine ridge indian reservation in south dakota 
i feel that for the survival of our people we are going to 
have to come together iron cloud said it is a very historical 
event 
duncan was critical of a utah legislative task force set up to 
look into allegations that nonindians living on the uteouray 
reservation in uintah and duchesne counties are the victims of 
civil rights violations nonindians also complain about a sliding 
10 percent tribal severance tax on oil and gas taken from indian 
lands 
nonindians who live on our lands need to recognize our laws 
just like we recognize theirs when we leave the reservation he 
said we are fighting for a way of life all were asking is to 
leave our treaties alone 
the sovereignty of tribal nations has been under attack since 
1492 said roger a jourdain chairman of the red lake minn 
chippewa tribe 
