<TEXT>
the puyallup tribe signed away its claim to 
much of its traditional land saturday in exchange for cash 
promises of jobs and education and a chunk of tacomas industrial 
waterfront 
this is one of the most important events in our tribes 
history said tribe chairman henry john at a packed downtown 
ceremony 
john said he did not expect the 162 million land claims 
settlement to solve all problems that have divided the indian and 
white communities over the past century but he said it gives a 
framework for resolving future disagreements 
under the agreement the secondlargest native land settlement 
in us history the puyallups are abandoning their claim to 20000 
acres at the mouth of the puyallup river the land now forms the 
port of tacoma and most of the citys industrial land 
it once was part of the tribes reservation but most was lost 
to white settlers in the late 1800s and early 1900s 
in return the tribe will receive a package that includes 900 
acres up to 20000 cash for each of the tribes 1500 members 
and trusts that promise a future of jobs education and security 
the only bigger native land settlement in the united states was the 
alaska native claims act 
the signing ceremony which included speeches by dignitaries and 
colorfully costumed dancers performing to tribal drums took place 
after the tribes attorneys appeared in us district court an hour 
earlier to ask for dismissal of a landclaims lawsuit filed in the 
early 1980s 
john bell attorney for the tribe told us judge john 
coughenour that of all the features in the agreement approved by 
tribe members in 1988 the most important was the tribes 
recognition by the larger community 
the tribe and its rights have gained a measure of respect 
he said 
sen daniel inouye dhawaii and chairman of the senate select 
committee on indian affairs said that while many of the injustices 
against indians will never be undone the puyallup agreement is a 
model for settling similar disputes 
people in tacoma have demonstrated there is an alternative 
to endless court battles over tribal claims he said 
inouye who made a dozen visits to tacoma to help in 
negotiations said he was approached by rep norm dicks dwash 
in 1987 to help resolve the dispute after a 1986 tribal vote 
rejected a proposed settlement he said he found bitterness on both 
sides but felt it was an opportunity to show negotiation could 
work 
both sides would have to put their necks on the line he 
said 
while some tribal members will undoubtedly squander their share 
of the payoff the majority will act responsibly because they 
know their brothers and sisters in indian country will be 
watching inouye said 
dicks said the cooperation built into the agreement benefits not 
only the tribe but also landholders in tacoma bypassed by 
development because indian claims clouded land titles 
the terms of this settlement will make the puyallup tribe a 
major economic force in our community he said 
eight to ten indian protesters appeared outside the courthouse 
and the downtown hotel where the signing ceremony took place with 
signs that read poor still poor puyallup tribe never gave 
us nothing and no delays pay today 
the protesters said they feared they would not get their 
individual payments the tribe has said it will probably be at 
least 60 days before the payments are made 
of the 162 million 51 million goes for dredging blair 
waterway on the industrial waterfront and improving roads in the 
area including some that lead to 240 waterfront acres deeded to 
the tribe 
other major elements of the settlement include 
24 million to provide the onetime payments to tribe members 
22 million in a permanent trust fund for social health and 
welfare needs of the tribe 
37 million as total value of the 900 acres the tribe will 
receive 
35 million for job training for 265 puyallups and jobs 
promised for 115 tribe members in pierce county privatesector 
businesses 
115 million for economic development 
10 million for fisheries enhancement 
contributors to the settlement include the federal government 
washington state private businesses and nearby municipalities 
