<TEXT>
the department of health and human services on 
friday proposed new regulations putting the burden on the states to 
ensure that the mentally ill and mentally retarded get appropriate 
care in nursing homes 
the proposal would implement a law passed by congress in 1987 
requiring states to set up programs to screen nursing home 
applicants and find more appropriate placements for mentally ill 
and mentally retarded applicants who do not need nursing facility 
care 
another proposed regulation would require nursing homes to meet 
new training and competency standards for nurse aides 
the screening requirement took effect jan 1 1989 although no 
regulations were in place the health care financing administration 
notified state medicaid directors at the time that compliance was 
required and provided preliminary guidance to the states 
failure of a nursing home to meet the terms of the screening 
requirement could result in its termination from the medicaid 
program 
the proposed rule outlines the specific details of the 
preadmission screening programs and requires an annual review of 
current nursing home residents with mental illness and retardation 
in the annual reviews nursing homes are to identify mentally 
ill and retarded patients who need active treatment for those 
conditions 
if a patient requires active treatment and has been in a nursing 
home less than 30 months and doesnt need nursing facility care 
the state must arrange for active treatment of the patient in a 
setting that more appropriately meets his needs 
nursing home residents who have been in a home for more than 30 
months but do not need nursing care may opt to stay there and the 
state must provide or arrange for active treatment under the rule 
nursing homes have been concerned about the screening 
requirement and many said last year that mentally ill and retarded 
patients would be turned out of nursing homes into the streets 
linda keegan a spokeswoman for the american health care 
association said that we didnt see a lot of problems with the 
preadmission screening but we dont know to what extent that was 
because of the flexibility states have had because detailed 
regulations arent yet in place 
under the proposal concerning training of nurse aides states 
must establish registries of nurse aides who meet training and 
competency requirements including any findings that a nurse aide 
has abused or neglected patients or stolen property 
both sets of rules were published in the federal register and 
each will have a 60day comment period before final rules are 
issued 
</TEXT>
