<TEXT>
the energy department plans to restart a 
savannah river nuclear weapons reactor this year without bringing 
it into compliance with the nations main water pollution law two 
environmental groups said friday 
the natural resources defense council and the energy research 
foundation which contend the reactor is not needed made the 
allegation in a letter to energy secretary james d watkins 
the groups notified the department that they would sue if 
watkins carried out his plan to restart the k reactor at 
savannah river before completing work on a cooling tower the 
tower scheduled for completion in 1992 would bring the facility 
into compliance with the federal water pollution control act of 
1972 
catherine kaliniak a department spokeswoman said doe was in 
compliance with the clean water act under a consent order issued by 
south carolina 
during the construction of the cooling tower k reactor can 
be restarted and operated under the consent order issued by the 
state she said 
the savannah river production site near aiken sc along the 
banks of the savannah river is the nations only source of 
tritium a gas needed in nuclear warheads all three reactors there 
have been closed for nearly two years for safety reasons 
watkins recently said he expected the k reactor to be back 
in production by the end of this year although he cautioned that 
the timing is not firm the two other reactors to be restarted in 
1991 circulate their heated water through manmade lakes before it 
reaches the river system 
the environmental groups contend that untreated water from the 
k reactor at temperatures of up to 180 degrees interferes 
with fish migration and causes other environmental damage the 
reactor began operating in 1954 
without the cooling tower this reactor will dump scalding 
water directly into natural streams and damage valuable wetlands 
said frances hart chairwoman of the energy research foundation a 
public interest group in columbia sc 
in their letter to watkins the environmental groups said the 
water pollution control act provides an alternative to building the 
cooling tower it says the president may exempt any federal 
facility from the law if he believes it is necessary to protect 
paramount national interests 
president bush has made no such determination 
dan reicher an attorney for the natural resources defense 
council said such an exemption would be inappropriate because two 
other reactors at savannah river could be restarted to meet the 
tritium requirements without violating the water pollution law 
