<TEXT>
a new un report painted a bleak picture friday 
of the worlds 42 poorest countries becoming poorer with economic 
growth rates lagging behind the population explosion 
it blamed domestic policy failures and lack of international 
help and urged enormous endeavors to reverse the decline 
the secretariat of the united nations conference on trade and 
development which released the report called for a relief program 
that would double development assistance and eliminate bilateral 
debt 
average annual growth of the countries gross domestic product 
was 23 percent during 198088 compared to a 72 percent target 
set by a special un conference in 1981 according to the 250page 
report 
agricultural production affected in some countries by drought 
or floods grew by 2 percent annually half the targeted growth at 
the same time the population increased by 24 percent every year 
to a present estimated total of 440 million 
this would reach 882 million by the year 2015 if present 
demographic trends continue for the third world as a whole the 
population increase is expected to total 65 percent the next 25 
years to about 48 billion the report said 
the 42 countries surveyed were afghanistan bangladesh benin 
bhutan botswana burkina faso burundi cape verde central 
african republic chad comoros north yemen south yemen 
djibouti equatorial guinea ethiopia gambia guinea 
guineabissau haiti kiribati laos lesotho malawi maldives 
mali mauritania mozambique burma nepal niger ruanda samoa 
sao tome and principe sierra leone somalia sudan togo tuvalu 
uganda tanzania and vanuatu 
their share of world exports declined to 03 percent in 1988 
down from 14 percent in 1960 total outstanding debt doubled from 
1982 to 1988 to 69 billion 
a prime factor was the declining trend in world prices for 
primary commodities that still make up about twothirds of their 
total exports the report noted 
but it also said domestic policies had been an important 
factor in restricting export development 
the report said rising demand for food water land firewood 
and other natural resources had further aggravated an already 
precarious ecological balance in many of the countries 
it said a new class of displaced persons have emerged in these 
countries in the 1980s environmental refugees 
growing human pressure on the natural environment has either 
rendered ecosystems more vulnerable or triggered off a 
selfreinforcing process of natural degradation or both as a 
result more people are affected by natural catastrophes such as 
landslides cyclones earthquakes and flood than before 
domestic economic adjustment programs failed to get enough 
outside financial support and achieved at most limited 
success the report said lack of financial resources also forced 
cutbacks on spending for social services 
it said the causes of the generally dismal performance are to 
a very large extent related to domestic policy shortcomings coupled 
with insufficient and inadequate international support 
a special un conference is to deal with the situation in the 
least developed countries in paris next september and consider 
possible action 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

