lee apologized for the mistake i have committed and promised 
to work for greater wildlife protection measures by the taiwanese 
government he could have faced as much as 30 years in prison and 
1 million in fines 
us fishermen have complained that taiwanese and others are 
overfishing salmon by catching them in driftnets supposedly set 
for other species such as squid 
the case was based on the lacey act which bars the importing of 
illegally caught fish or wildlife the judge ruled that a taiwanese 
administrative ban on salmon fishing by taiwanese vessels 
constituted a foreign law making the fish contraband under us 
law 
defense attorney mark mestel said he would appeal that ruling 
which resulted in lee pleading guilty to conspiracy smuggling and 
moneylaundering 
mr lee could not have been prosecuted in taiwan because the 
regulation applied only to the vessel operator and skipper he told 
dimmick the fish broker could not be punished 
however assistant us attorney robert chadwell said lee knew 
he was violating us law during the sixmonth sting that led 
to his arrest 
the sting which involved agents from the national marine 
fisheries service coast guard and customs service began in march 
1989 after lee offered to sell a us seafood processor large 
quantities of salmon caught in driftnets used by taiwanese vessels 
to catch squid 
lee who had been in business about two years subsequently 
agreed to sell an undercover agent 500 metric tons of salmon for 
13 million 
the trap was sprung july 18 as two taiwanese squid fishing boats 
delivered salmon to a refrigerator ship chartered by two undercover 
agents in the middle of the pacific ocean three of lees 
associates were arrested on the us vessel and lee and two others 
were arrested after examining 13 million in a bank safe deposit 
box in seattle and leaving with 330000 
the 66000 lee was ordered to repay represented money one of 
his associates had accepted as an advance payment 
