<TEXT>
trained to believe that general recessions are 
inevitable many economists have searched diligently over the past 
two years for supporting evidence 
occasionally they think they find that evidence and they make a 
quick grab for it but then just as a youngster opens his squeezed 
fist and finds he didnt catch the grasshopper they discover they 
have nothing 
month by month bit by bit the evidence seems to be presented 
lagging car sales lower stock prices weak retail sales lowered 
investor confidence home starts off then the opposite occurs the 
numbers reverse themselves no trend there 
its been that way for two years now but rather than being 
discouraged some searchers are more convinced than ever that the 
beast is out there ready to pounce its been seven long 
years they say it has to come 
in fact some of them are convinced it must come recessions are 
not all bad these theorists say recessions might even be 
necessary to kill off excesses of demand or expectations or 
borrowing they are corrective 
the theorists are correct about the seven years measured 
nationally no recession has occurred in that time national 
figures they say are the only evidence thats the way they were 
trained thats the way they believe 
national statistics dont lie they say and you tend to agree 
in spite of lapses corrections revisions and adjustments united 
states economic figures are usually conceded to be the worlds most 
accurate 
no they may not lie but some critics contend the economic 
numbers hide the facts at least from those who read them in a 
certain way from those who by habit look for certain evidence and 
ignore other evidence 
the habitual way of proving recession is to examine the national 
readings for gross national product which is the total output of 
goods and services if the gnp shrinks for two successive quarters 
you have a recession 
by that definition there has been no recession since the fall of 
1982 
but what about regional recessions or economic shrinkages that 
affected some of the country but not all of it or industrywide 
recessions that didnt spread to the general economy by that 
measure there have been lots of them 
in that time period farm states have had a recession 
simultaneously mining and manufacturing states were down too 
several states had deep recessions due to oil pricing real estate 
has been off in several areas 
at one point sindlinger amp co an economics researcher told 
clients that more than 30 states could be considered in recession 
but this important recession never showed up in the national 
numbers coastal booms offset it 
those who work in specific industries can relate their recession 
woes among these industries farming mining homebuilding 
defense automobiles remember the oil patch problems and the rust 
belt 
right now there is a recession in the securities industry more 
than half the brokerage houses on the new york stock exchange lost 
money in the fourth quarter of 1989 savings and loans are in bad 
shape new england banks too 
to say there has been no recession in seven years is to ignore 
the evidence of regional and industry recessions this is the 
contention of those who support the rolling readjustment or 
traveling recession theory 
they say that for reasons not fully understood perhaps it has 
something to do with a better understanding of economics at the 
federal reserve the nation has had its recession here and there a 
bit at a time piecemeal 
the beast they say might have changed its habits rather than 
crashing out of the jungle with a leap and a roar it stalks the 
edges of the economy nibbling here and there getting its way that 
way and covering its tracks 
