<TEXT>
wall street has shown it is capable of defying 
the gravitational pull of the sliding tokyo stock market 
challenging notions of global interdependence 
but many securities strategists say it is foolish to conclude 
the two largest stock markets are going separate ways 
the securities boom of the 1980s gave rise to the view that the 
world has become one big 24hour trading floor with buying and 
selling moving seamlessly each day from the far east to western 
europe to the united states insomniac traders are linked around 
the globe by telephone and computer 
the most powerful and scary example of this globalization 
occurred in the october 1987 market collapse as panic selling 
reverberated from continent to continent 
but in the past month or so tidal waves sweeping the tokyo 
market have turned into ripples or less by the time they 
reached new york naysayers of globalization said the socalled 
inextricable links were unraveling 
some strategists even argued that tokyos malaise is new yorks 
health tonic they argue that japanese investors panicky about 
further weakening of stocks in their own country have been selling 
them and buying us shares instead 
some of the trading sessions last week seemed to reflect this 
theory on monday for example wall street dropped initially but 
shrugged off the thirdbiggest daily drop in tokyos key nikkei 
stock average the dow jones average of 30 industrials finished the 
day higher 
on tuesday after another steep dive in tokyo the new york 
market finished only mildly lower 
on thursday when the tokyo market sank to the lowest close 
since christmas eve of 1988 wall street sold off as well but the 
drop was by no means catastrophic some strategists said it was a 
technical correction 
i think weve delinked ourselves from tokyo said larry 
wachtel an analyst for prudentialbache securities inc theyre 
two different markets now 
nonetheless wachtel and others believe that could change if 
japanese investors were forced to sell their us stocks to raise 
cash for obligations at home 
if the declines in the japanese markets become too severe 
thats when all of the markets around the world will be 
negatively impacted said hugh johnson senior vice president of 
first albany corp in albany ny at some point theyre going 
to look like theyve recoupled 
the tight connections between the japanese and us economies 
mean their markets wont go separate ways indefinitely some 
observers believe 
the resilience wall street has been showing in the face of 
tokyos travails springs largely from foreign institutional 
investors mainly japanese and european who have moved chunks of 
capital out of the tokyo market and into new york 
a major reason for the decline in japan has been the weakening 
yen which makes stocks there worth less and increases inflation 
the bank of japan raised its key discount rate by one percentage 
point tuesday to 525 percent the fourth in a series of increases 
intended mainly to fight inflation but it didnt do much to help 
the faltering japanese currency 
against that background foreign investors have been seeking 
comfort in our financial markets johnson said 
thats why even negative economic news in the united states 
like government reports last week on rising inflation and an 
intractable trade deficit havent perturbed wall street too much 
the dollar is relatively strong at the moment and the economic 
grass for now seems to be greener on the american side 
