the 25th floor of the south tower of the 
luxurious world financial center is empty save for a few boxes so 
are the 26th 27th and 28th floors 
in the booming mid1980s merrill lynch amp co expected to fill 
the space easily the nations largest securities firm booked two 
full towers in the ultramodern complex in lower manhattan that 
opened in 1986 using conservative estimates of employment growth 
then merrill scaled back to one tower plus about half the 
second after the 1987 stock market crash even that was too much 
and now the firm plans to sublet nine floors including the four 
undeveloped ones 
on wall street and broad street and greenwich street and 
battery place a securities industry recession has created an 
officespace glut in the worlds premier financial district 
vacancy rates are soaring in the maze of silver office towers 
and aging stone monoliths where stock trading began almost 200 
years ago under a buttonwood tree property brokers compare the 
slump to the mid1970s when new york teetered on bankruptcy 
were still headed south said robert fr ballard an 
executive vice president with the real estate firm cushman amp 
wakefield who has worked in the wall street building market since 
1959 we havent bottomed out yet 
manhattan real estate brokers say the vacancy rate in the 
downtown financial district is approaching 20 percent vs 8 
percent to 12 percent in 1985 during the securities industry boom 
put another way the 14 million square feet of available office 
space downtown equals three empty buildings each as big as a 
110story world trade center tower 
the glut is expected to worsen because hundreds of thousands of 
square feet to be abandoned by firms such as merrill shearson 
lehman hutton inc salomon inc and collapsed drexel burnham 
lambert inc havent been tallied yet 
unprecedented growth in stock trading and investment banking 
gave rise to handoverfist hiring and expansion by wall street 
firms in the 1980s 
average daily trading volume on the new york stock exchange shot 
up from 322 million shares in 1979 to 189 million shares in 1987 
while employment in in new yorks securities and commodities 
industries grew from 74000 to 163000 
during that period wall street firms set ambitious expansion 
plans tied to the seemingly limitless possibilities of another 
boom building world headquarters seemed logical to accomodate 
technological advances that required more space for more computers 
for more trading into the 21st century 
many of the financial firms dont indulge in what we call 
