was growing by 13 percent annually it booked the world financial 
center space anticipating only half that growth but since the 
crash merrill has slashed its work force back to a 1980 level 
more cuts are planned 
the firm took a 470 million charge against earnings last 
quarter for its restructuring 220 million to cover real estate 
commitments nearly all of that in new york 
the growth has certainly gone in the other direction 
merrill spokesman fred yager said our fixed costs have been 
reduced considerably and one of our biggest fixed costs is real 
estate 
for the real estate market the gluts the thing while modern 
office spaces such as the world financial center and world trade 
center complexes are almost fully occupied older buildings are 
bearing the brunt as firms move out 
the average asking rent downtown is falling but not in 
proportion to available space brokers say topline offices still 
command around 35 per square foot among the highest in the 
country some prices for older buildings though have fallen into 
the single digits just like in the 1970s 
brokers estimate the downtown vacancy rate will climb well above 
20 percent once a rash of moves some across new york waterways to 
cheaper brooklyn or new jersey are completed in the mid70s 
the rate was about 25 percent brokers said 
among the untallied moves the securities industry automation 
corps move to new quarters abandoning 200000 square feet 
salomons shift to 7 world trade center leaving 500000 square 
