<TEXT>
joseph hazelwoods future seemed less murky 
after a jury acquitted the skipper of serious charges stemming from 
the alaska oil spill but lawyers say the verdict may dump more 
trouble onto his exboss exxon corp 
i guess the jurors thought it was exxons fault and decided 
not make the captain the goat said melvin belli a celebrity 
attorney famous for winning multimilliondollar judgments who 
represents 500 clients suing exxon 
it wont hurt my case at all he said in a telephone 
interview after the hazelwood verdict was announced this past week 
it might help my case they let the captain off now lets get 
the people who are really responsible 
the captain of the exxon valdez tanker that hit a reef a year 
ago and spewed oil into prince william sound was convicted of only 
a simple misdemeanor count of negligence for his role in the 
nations worst oil spill he was sentenced to help clean up the 
mess and pay 50000 in restitution 
jurors at a trial in anchorage alaska said there wasnt enough 
evidence to convict him on the more substantial counts of criminal 
mischief reckless endangerment and operating a vessel while drunk 
the verdict stunned much of the nation including attorneys who 
said the lynchmob atmosphere created by the oil spill had made 
convictions seem a foregone conclusion 
exxon which fired hazelwood after the disaster said it was 
pleased his ordeal was over and that the verdict suggested the 
grounding was an accident hazelwood even said he would try to 
renegotiate his old job back 
but specialists in corporate liability law said hazelwoods 
conviction on the negligence charge might be bad news for exxon 
because it could be used by the hundreds of plaintiffs suing the 
company for civil damages as solid evidence that the company 
through one of its employees was to blame 
some also suggested that the jurys failure to convict on the 
more serious charges didnt mean they wouldnt be raised again in 
civil litigation in which the rules of evidence are much less 
stringent than in criminal proceedings 
exxon gets very little benefit out of this said david 
leebron a professor of corporate liability law at columbia 
university law school 
exxon would be responsible for the negligence of its 
employees he said they might have been hoping that the 
employee did something so unpredictable it would get them out of 
liability so in this case the jury finding of negligence hurts 
them 
belli whose clients range from alaskan boatbuilders to japanese 
canneries hurt by a postspill fishing ban around the alaskan 
coast said the verdict only strengthened his legal arsenal he 
predicted exxon would attempt to settle most of the lawsuits 
the damages arent measured in millions he said theyre 
in billions 
daniel d polsby a professor of law at northwestern university 
in chicago speculated that the hazelwood verdict would shift the 
focus of litigation away from who was responsible now he said 
the question is going to be who has got a right to complain 
that could mean many years of tangled lawsuits and questions 
over who was hurt financially by the spill and what will be 
required to clean it up exxon already has spent about 2 billion 
in a cleanup but its future liability is undetermined 
some lawyers suggested exxon also faces the tricky problem of 
whether to rehire hazelwood he was dismissed for violating company 
policy after postspill tests revealed he had been legally drunk 
but the jury said the evidence wasnt there to back that up 
andrew kramer chairman of the labor section at the law firm 
jones day reavis amp pogue said if exxon rehired hazelwood it 
might undermine the companys contention that the skipper acted 
irresponsibly 
on the other hand kramer said exxon executives might reason 
that if we dont rehire him he is a potential witness against 
us 
in other business and economic news this past week 
southland corp the nations largest convenience store 
operator agreed to sell control to a japanese company because of 
crushing debt burdens stemming from a junkbondfinanced buyout 
the deal announced by the founder of the 7eleven chain was one of 
the most dramatic examples of credit crises faced by us companies 
that have relied heavily on junk financing 
president bushs savings amp loan bailout plan hit a potentially 
crippling snag when a judge prevented a government takeover of an 
ailing chicago thrift on grounds that federal regulators in charge 
of the bailout were appointed unconstitutionally an appeals court 
temporarily blocked the order and bush moved to blunt it as well by 
nominating a new thriftoffice director to be confirmed by the 
senate 
japans mighty financial markets plunged bolstering the view 
that what goes up must come down but the decline had a limited 
impact on us stock prices reviving the question of whether the 
globalization of securities trading is as important as earlier 
believed 
