<TEXT>
winnebago industries inc reported 
friday that its losses more than doubled in the second quarter of 
its fiscal year and disclosed problems arranging credit with banks 
and financial institutions 
the 53 million loss in the quarter ended feb 24 reflected a 
weak market for motor homes losses from a new division that makes 
trucks for delivery businesses and continued losses from its 
cyclesat subsidiary that delivers commercials to television 
stations by satellite 
frank rolfes who follows winnebago for the minneapolis 
securities firm of dain bosworth said the results were in line 
with his projections which are very negative 
theyre not doing very well down there he said it 
doesnt appear to be getting better 
on wall street the report appeared to be shrugged off as the 
new york stock exchangelisted winnebago ended the day unchanged at 
525 a share 
john k hanson the founder and chairman of the forest city 
manufacturer said recent negotiations with the companys banks and 
financial institutions failed to achieve acceptable credit 
terms 
as a result winnebago has reduced its outstanding shortterm 
borrowing through the liquidation of the companys marketable 
securities portfolio and sale of winnebago acceptance corporations 
dealer receivables hanson said 
winnebago acceptance corp provides financing to buyers of its 
motor homes and recreational vehicles its receivables are the loan 
agreements it holds 
spokeswoman sheila davis said the company had sold its entire 
securities portfolio 
the company did not release its securities losses or put a value 
on the securities sold but ms davis said that at the end of its 
first fiscal quarter winnebago had 306 million in cash and 
securities 
rolfes said he did not believe the company was in danger of 
collapse because it has little longterm debt but added theyve 
got to do something to turn things around 
in its annual report the company listed total shortterm debt 
of about 57 million and longterm debt of 64 million as of aug 
26 1989 
rolfes said winnebago had been losing money on its securities 
portfolio for years and may have decided it was putting that 
investment to better use by buying down its shortterm debt to 
reduce interest expenses 
the 53 million loss in the second quarter of the fiscal year 
came to 21 cents a share and compared with a loss of almost 26 
million or 10 cents a share in the same period a year earlier 
revenue for the period fell almost 25 percent to 806 million from 
1071 million 
the results for the quarter were caused by losses in rv 
operations due to lower motor home sales volume substantial 
inventive and promotion costs a shift in product mix to lower 
priced motor homes and continuing losses by winnebago subsidiary 
cyclesat startup costs for the commercial vehicle division and 
losses in financial investments hanson said 
for the first half of the fiscal year winnebago reported a loss 
of nearly 10 million or 40 cents a share compared with a profit 
of 63 million or 25 cents a share in the same period a year 
earlier revenue fell by 32 percent to 1596 million from 2351 
million 
